AB  - We studied two wetland plant community types that occur on flat lake terraces in the Eastern Pamir mountains (Tajikistan, Central Asia). We selected 13 homogeneous patches of salt marsh vegetation dominated by Blysmus rufus (Huds.) Link, and 20 homogeneous patches of saline small sedge meadow. From each patch we took soil and biomass samples which were analysed in the laboratory. We used delta O-13 and delta N-15 values for plant biomass to determine the type of nutrient limitation and to characterise dominant species, and we assessed the impact of detrital input on the CNP stoichiometry of biomass. Biomass delta C-13 was typical for plants growing under low partial pressure of CO2; while delta N-15 was very high, especially in the leaves of Carex orbicularis Boott. N limitation was indicated for the majority of sampled sites, yet we found no significant correlation between delta O-13 or delta N-15 and N/P quotient. There were pronounced differences in delta N-15 between species, the lowest values being recorded for Carex microglochin Wahlenb. No significant influence of detrital inputs on the chemical composition of plant biomass was detected.
