AB  - Microbial biofilms are complex communities of bacteria, protozoa, microalgae, and micrometazoa in a polymer matrix on submerged surfaces. Their development is integrative of environmental conditions, being affected by local biodiversity, the availability of organic matter and inorganic nutrients (bottom-up), and the presence or absence of biofilm grazers (top-down). We seek to utilize information content of microbial biofilms where they develop as indicators of ecosystem status. Our two major hypotheses are: 1) microbial biofilms will exhibit habitat specificity as a result of top-down and bottom-up controls of community structure and function, and 2) the integrative nature of the biofilms will reflect conditions of specific habitats as a result of changes to top-down and bottom-up forces. Various endpoints of community structure and function include bulk chemical characterization, total heterotrophic activity, phosphatase activity, nitrogen fixation/denitrification rates, phospholipid methyl ester profiles, and molecular probing for diversity of organisms and expression patterns of genes coding for enzymes associated with biogeochemical cycling. Initial results suggest that these microbial communities, developed on standardized acrylic plate samplers, have habitat fidelity, even within short spatial scales. Total material by carbon, nitrogen, protein, carbohydrate, lipid and DNA content, or optical density of dried biofilms show dramatic differences for oyster reef vs. non-oyster reef and salt marsh vs. open water habitats. Spatial variability within biofilms assessed by optical density may be a useful indicator at a gross scale of analysis, while phospholipid patterns appear to provide better resolution. We optimized extraction of nucleic acids from microbial biofilms by comparison of a variety of commercial and traditional procedures, based on total DNA yield and relative proportion of high molecular weight DNA.
