AB  - The secondary production of Nereis diversicolor and Scoloplos armiger (Annelida, Polychaeta) was studied at Stiffkey saltmarshes (north Norfolk coast). Production estimation on the basis of monthly sampling (August 1992-July 1993) gives 17.91 g C m(-2) y(-1) for N: diversicolor, 3.37 g C m(-2) y(-1) for S. armiger. Oxygen consumption of individuals was studied using a respirometer at four temperatures (5, 10, 15 and 20 degrees C). At 15 degrees C, the relationships between O-2 consumption (mg h(-1)) and body dry weight (mg) is Y=0.003X(0.695) for S. armiger and Y=0.003X(0.498) for N. diversicolor. Ammonia excretion of S. armiger tends to increase with decreasing temperature whereas it increases from 5 to 15 degrees C for N. diversicolor. Carbon loss through respiration for the sampling period is estimated at 32 g C m(-2) y(-1) for S. armiger, and 31.7 g C m(-2) y(-1) for N: diversicolor. About 20 % of the potential supply of phytobenthic carbon in the marsh would be converted by the populations of both species. Estimations of carbon and nitrogen budgets of S. armiger are discussed.
